    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Attractive, sprawling perennial daisy with leathery leaves that are divided into 3-7 elliptical lobes. The leaf margins tend to be rolled under, with the upper surfaces smooth and the undersides white-felted. The large, attractive, compound flowers can be either yellow or orange and the petal-like rays each have variable dark and white marks at the base and a stripe along the underside.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9558",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Typically reaches a height of 20-40 cm, leaves up to 110 mm long and flowers up to 40 mm diameter.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9559",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Restricted distribution along the coast from Namaqualand to about Mossel Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9560",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Common on coastal rocks and sands dunes where can extends almost down to high water mark. &nbsp;Colour vary variable and most commonly yellow rather than the orange depicted here.</p><p>Plants in this genus are spectacular when in flower, attract a variety of pollinators and are popular in coastal gardens or in containers.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9561",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9562",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers November to February. The seeds are small and easily dispersed by wing. Patches also spread via rhizomes leading to dense patches of flowers of the same colour.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9563",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>There are several similar regional species in this genus. This species is easily confused with the Dune gazania <i>G. rigens</i>, which is also common along the coast, but ranges along the south and east (but not west) coasts into Mozambique. That species also usually has simple, lance-shaped leaves (sometimes 5-lobed) and has yellow to orange rays that may or may not have a single black mark at the base.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9564",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
